\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}A plan (typically) doesn\'92t fit on a page and trying to expand and contract summary tasks to get something that does fit on a page is fiddly and the end result is often not great.  It\'92s hard to get the level of detail right and still be able to understand the plan.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The GANTT format with one activity on each line is fine for working with the plan but not great for presenting it.  In practice you\'92d like to be able to make better use of the space by having multiple activities on the same line if they don\'92t overlap, and by having a sequence of related activities on the same line this can make for an easy to interpret visual.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}There is a lot of visual information shown in MS Project or other project management apps which (again) is useful for managing the plan but not for presenting it.  The various types of dependency arrows, percentage complete indicators etc. can be useful but when trying to present to non project managers you usually want a simple but informative representation of the plan.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}You often need to include in a slide deck (in fact this is by far the most common way I have had to share a plan outside the immediate project team and often even with them), and there\'92s no way of creating a visual from MSP which is of a high enough quality for that - particularly if presenting to senior stakeholders who want something which looks good and is easy to understand.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}So the app takes as input a project plan, at the moment as an Excel import from a plan exported to Excel.  It then allows the user to pick which activities from the plan to include in a visual, to place these within a swimlane, and to lay them out to make a visual which will work for their use case.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}If the plan updates, the updated plan can be imported and the visual will be updated and can be adjusted if required.  The intention is that once the visual is set up, which should be fairly easy, maintaining it will be a very easy task.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}An appropriate timeline can be added at the top of the visual (e.g. months, quarters etc).\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Formatting (colours for activities, swimlanes, timelines and text) can be set by the user.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}At the moment, the visual is an image and to capture it you take a screen shot.  Obviously this is a short term approach and will be improved upon, but it\'92s still useful and the image can be pasted into a PowerPoint slide to create a highly compelling visual representation of a plan.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Multiple visuals can be created for the same plan, to support different use cases.  So maybe a milestone plan\
